Note: ========================================
Note: CSS Translation Tests
Note: ========================================
Note: Test suite for CSS frontend + backend

Note: Part of the Translation translation system - CSS tests

Note: Tests:
Note:   - CSS lexing (selectors, properties, values, at-rules)
Note:   - CSS parsing (rules, declarations, selectors, functions)
Note:   - CSS→HIR translation (preserving structure and semantics)
Note:   - HIR→CSS generation (producing valid CSS)
Note:   - Round-trip translation (CSS → HIR → CSS)
Note: ========================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/css/css_lexer.runa" as Lexer
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/css/css_parser.runa" as Parser
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/css/css_to_hir.runa" as Frontend
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/css/hir_to_css.runa" as Backend
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir.runa" as HIR
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout

Note: ========================================
Note: Test Runner
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level driver for the CSS translation suite. Runs eight tests in
dependency order: lexer, parser, CSS->HIR, HIR->CSS, and four
round-trip checks of increasing complexity (simple rule, complex
selectors, at-rules, CSS functions).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Print banner, call each test_* proc serially. Inline [PASS]/[FAIL]
output is emitted by each test rather than aggregated here.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- All 8 tests emit [PASS] -> clean suite
- Any test emits [FAIL] -> visible in CI output
@End TestCases

Process called "run_all_css_tests":
    Note: Run all CSS translation tests

    proc print_string with "=== CSS Translation Test Suite ===\n"

    proc test_css_lexer
    proc test_css_parser
    proc test_css_to_hir
    proc test_hir_to_css
    proc test_round_trip_simple_rule
    proc test_round_trip_complex_selectors
    proc test_round_trip_at_rules
    proc test_round_trip_functions

    proc print_string with "\n=== All CSS Tests Complete ===\n"
End Process

Note: ========================================
Note: Lexer Tests
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
Verifies the CSS lexer produces at least 12 tokens for a one-rule
stylesheet with two declarations (".button { color: #fff;
font-size: 16px; }"). The minimum count (12) is the structural floor:
. button { color : #fff ; font-size : 16px ; } — anything less
means the lexer fused or dropped tokens.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Build source ".button { color: #fff; font-size: 16px; }".
2. Create lexer, scan_tokens.
3. Read tokens list from lexer offset 40, count via List.size.
4. Print token count for diagnostics.
5. Assert count >= 12; print [PASS] or [FAIL].
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Two-declaration rule -> >= 12 tokens, [PASS]
- Lexer fuses identifier+colon -> count < 12, [FAIL] "insufficient tokens"
- Lexer drops hex color -> count < 12, [FAIL]
@End TestCases

Process called "test_css_lexer":
    Note: Test CSS lexer tokenization

    proc print_string with "\n--- Testing CSS Lexer ---\n"

    Note: Test basic CSS rule lexing
    Let css_code be proc create_string from StringCore with ".button { color: #fff; font-size: 16px; }"

    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with css_code
    proc scan_tokens from Lexer with lexer

    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40
    Let token_count be proc size from List with tokens

    proc print_string with "Token count: "
    proc print_integer from token_count
    proc print_string with "\n"

    Note: Verify expected tokens
    If token_count is greater than or equal to 12:
        proc print_string with "[PASS] CSS lexer tokenization\n"
    Otherwise:
        proc print_string with "[FAIL] CSS lexer tokenization - insufficient tokens\n"
    End If

    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    proc deallocate from Layout with css_code
End Process

Note: ========================================
Note: Parser Tests
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
Verifies the parser builds a stylesheet AST root from "h1 { color:
red; }". Checks both that the AST is non-null AND that its node_type
field equals 1 (CSS_STYLESHEET) so a regression where the parser
returns a non-null but wrongly-tagged node is caught.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Build "h1 { color: red; }", lex, parse -> ast.
2. If ast != 0: emit [PASS] stylesheet, then read memory_get_int64(ast, 0)
   and assert == 1 (CSS_STYLESHEET tag), emit [PASS] or [FAIL].
3. If ast == 0: emit [FAIL] stylesheet.
4. Clean up regardless.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- "h1 { color: red; }" -> non-null AST with node_type == 1, two [PASS] lines
- Parser returns null -> "[FAIL] CSS parser stylesheet"
- Wrong root tag -> "[FAIL] CSS parser AST node type"
@End TestCases

Process called "test_css_parser":
    Note: Test CSS parser AST construction

    proc print_string with "\n--- Testing CSS Parser ---\n"

    Note: Test rule parsing
    Let css_code be proc create_string from StringCore with "h1 { color: red; }"

    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with css_code
    proc scan_tokens from Lexer with lexer

    Let parser be proc create_parser from Parser with lexer
    Let ast be proc parse from Parser with parser

    If ast is not equal to 0:
        proc print_string with "[PASS] CSS parser stylesheet\n"

        Note: Verify AST structure
        Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 0
        If node_type is equal to 1:  Note: CSS_STYLESHEET = 1
            proc print_string with "[PASS] CSS parser AST node type (stylesheet)\n"
        Otherwise:
            proc print_string with "[FAIL] CSS parser AST node type\n"
        End If

        proc destroy_css_node from Parser with ast
    Otherwise:
        proc print_string with "[FAIL] CSS parser stylesheet\n"
    End If

    proc destroy_parser from Parser with parser
    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    proc deallocate from Layout with css_code
End Process

Note: ========================================
Note: CSS→HIR Translation Tests
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
Verifies the CSS->HIR pipeline produces a dictionary-shaped HIR with
a "type" field. Uses "p { margin: 0; }" as the canonical minimal
rule. The dictionary-with-type check catches a regression where the
translator returns a non-null but malformed HIR node.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Lex+parse "p { margin: 0; }" -> ast.
2. Create translation context, translate_css_to_hir(context, ast) -> hir_node.
3. If hir_node != 0: emit [PASS], then assert get_hir_node_type ==
   7 (HIR_DICTIONARY_LITERAL), then assert "type" key exists via
   get_dictionary_value.
4. Three nested checks each emit their own [PASS] or [FAIL] line.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- "p { margin: 0; }" -> dict HIR with type key, three [PASS] lines
- Translator returns 0 -> "[FAIL] CSS→HIR translation"
- HIR is not dictionary -> "[FAIL] HIR node type"
- Dict missing "type" -> "[FAIL] HIR dictionary missing 'type' field"
@End TestCases

Process called "test_css_to_hir":
    Note: Test CSS→HIR translation

    proc print_string with "\n--- Testing CSS→HIR Translation ---\n"

    Note: Test simple rule translation
    Let css_code be proc create_string from StringCore with "p { margin: 0; }"

    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with css_code
    proc scan_tokens from Lexer with lexer

    Let parser be proc create_parser from Parser with lexer
    Let ast be proc parse from Parser with parser

    If ast is not equal to 0:
        Let context be proc create_translation_context from Frontend
        Let hir_node be proc translate_css_to_hir from Frontend with context, ast

        If hir_node is not equal to 0:
            proc print_string with "[PASS] CSS→HIR translation\n"

            Note: Verify HIR is dictionary
            Let node_type be proc get_hir_node_type from HIR with hir_node
            If node_type is equal to 7:  Note: HIR_DICTIONARY_LITERAL = 7
                proc print_string with "[PASS] HIR node type (dictionary)\n"

                Note: Verify "type" field exists
                Let type_key be proc create_string from StringCore with "type"
                Let type_value be proc get_dictionary_value from HIR with hir_node, type_key
                proc deallocate from Layout with type_key

                If type_value is not equal to 0:
                    proc print_string with "[PASS] HIR dictionary has 'type' field\n"
                Otherwise:
                    proc print_string with "[FAIL] HIR dictionary missing 'type' field\n"
                End If
            Otherwise:
                proc print_string with "[FAIL] HIR node type\n"
            End If

            proc destroy_hir_node from HIR with hir_node
        Otherwise:
            proc print_string with "[FAIL] CSS→HIR translation\n"
        End If

        proc destroy_translation_context from Frontend with context
        proc destroy_css_node from Parser with ast
    Otherwise:
        proc print_string with "[FAIL] CSS parsing for translation\n"
    End If

    proc destroy_parser from Parser with parser
    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    proc deallocate from Layout with css_code
End Process

Note: ========================================
Note: HIR→CSS Generation Tests
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
Reverse direction: construct a complete HIR for "div { width: 100px;
}" by hand and verify generate_css_from_hir produces non-null output.
This is the only test in the file that doesn't depend on the
frontend, so a parser bug can't mask an emitter regression.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Build hir_stylesheet via create_hir_dictionary_literal.
2. Add "type": "stylesheet" field via create_hir_string_literal +
   add_dictionary_entry.
3. Build rule_dict with "type": "rule", "selectors": ["div"],
   "declarations": [] (empty in this test).
4. Wrap rule_dict in rules_list, attach under "rules" key.
5. generate_css_from_hir(hir_stylesheet) -> generated_css.
6. Print generated_css for diagnostics; assert non-null.
Note: every allocated key string is deallocated immediately after
add_dictionary_entry returns since the HIR module copies key data.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- Hand-built HIR for "div { ... }" -> non-null CSS output, [PASS]
- Emitter returns null on well-formed HIR -> [FAIL]
- Emitter NPE on missing key -> would crash before [FAIL] line
@End TestCases

Process called "test_hir_to_css":
    Note: Test HIR→CSS generation

    proc print_string with "\n--- Testing HIR→CSS Generation ---\n"

    Note: Create HIR dictionary for simple CSS rule
    Let hir_stylesheet be proc create_hir_dictionary_literal from HIR

    Note: Add "type" field
    Let type_key be proc create_string from StringCore with "type"
    Let type_value_str be proc create_string from StringCore with "stylesheet"
    Let type_value be proc create_hir_string_literal from HIR with type_value_str
    proc add_dictionary_entry from HIR with hir_stylesheet, type_key, type_value
    proc deallocate from Layout with type_key
    proc deallocate from Layout with type_value_str

    Note: Add "rules" field (list with one rule)
    Let rules_key be proc create_string from StringCore with "rules"
    Let rules_list be proc create_hir_list_literal from HIR

    Note: Create a simple rule: div { width: 100px; }
    Let rule_dict be proc create_hir_dictionary_literal from HIR

    Let rule_type_key be proc create_string from StringCore with "type"
    Let rule_type_value_str be proc create_string from StringCore with "rule"
    Let rule_type_value be proc create_hir_string_literal from HIR with rule_type_value_str
    proc add_dictionary_entry from HIR with rule_dict, rule_type_key, rule_type_value
    proc deallocate from Layout with rule_type_key
    proc deallocate from Layout with rule_type_value_str

    Note: Add selectors to rule
    Let selectors_key be proc create_string from StringCore with "selectors"
    Let selectors_list be proc create_hir_list_literal from HIR

    Note: Create selector "div"
    Let selector_str be proc create_string from StringCore with "div"
    Let selector_lit be proc create_hir_string_literal from HIR with selector_str
    proc add_list_element from HIR with selectors_list, selector_lit
    proc deallocate from Layout with selector_str

    proc add_dictionary_entry from HIR with rule_dict, selectors_key, selectors_list
    proc deallocate from Layout with selectors_key

    Note: Add declarations
    Let declarations_key be proc create_string from StringCore with "declarations"
    Let declarations_list be proc create_hir_list_literal from HIR
    proc add_dictionary_entry from HIR with rule_dict, declarations_key, declarations_list
    proc deallocate from Layout with declarations_key

    proc add_list_element from HIR with rules_list, rule_dict

    proc add_dictionary_entry from HIR with hir_stylesheet, rules_key, rules_list
    proc deallocate from Layout with rules_key

    Note: Generate CSS from HIR
    Let generated_css be proc generate_css_from_hir from Backend with hir_stylesheet

    If generated_css is not equal to 0:
        proc print_string with "[PASS] HIR→CSS generation\n"
        proc print_string with "Generated CSS: "
        proc print_string from generated_css
        proc print_string with "\n"

        proc deallocate from Layout with generated_css
    Otherwise:
        proc print_string with "[FAIL] HIR→CSS generation\n"
    End If

    proc destroy_hir_node from HIR with hir_stylesheet
End Process

Note: ========================================
Note: Round-Trip Tests
Note: ========================================

@Reasoning:
End-to-end round-trip for the simplest practical CSS rule: two
declarations on the body element. Each pipeline stage is checked
individually so a failure log says exactly which stage broke
(parse, CSS->HIR, or HIR->CSS).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Build "body { margin: 0; padding: 0; }".
2. Lex+parse -> ast; null -> [FAIL] parsing, cleanup, Return.
3. translate_css_to_hir -> hir_node; null -> [FAIL] CSS->HIR, cleanup, Return.
4. generate_css_from_hir -> generated_css; null -> [FAIL] HIR->CSS,
   cleanup, Return.
5. Print original and generated CSS side-by-side, emit
   [PASS] "Round-trip simple rule (semantic check)".
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- "body { margin: 0; padding: 0; }" -> all three stages succeed, [PASS]
- Parser fails -> "[FAIL] Round-trip parsing"
- Translator returns 0 -> "[FAIL] Round-trip CSS→HIR"
- Emitter returns 0 -> "[FAIL] Round-trip HIR→CSS"
@End TestCases

Process called "test_round_trip_simple_rule":
    Note: Test round-trip: CSS → HIR → CSS (simple rule)

    proc print_string with "\n--- Testing Round-Trip: Simple Rule ---\n"

    Let original_css be proc create_string from StringCore with "body { margin: 0; padding: 0; }"

    Note: Parse original CSS
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with original_css
    proc scan_tokens from Lexer with lexer

    Let parser be proc create_parser from Parser with lexer
    Let ast be proc parse from Parser with parser

    If ast is equal to 0:
        proc print_string with "[FAIL] Round-trip parsing\n"
        proc destroy_parser from Parser with parser
        proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
        proc deallocate from Layout with original_css
        Return
    End If

    Note: Translate to HIR
    Let context be proc create_translation_context from Frontend
    Let hir_node be proc translate_css_to_hir from Frontend with context, ast

    If hir_node is equal to 0:
        proc print_string with "[FAIL] Round-trip CSS→HIR\n"
        proc destroy_translation_context from Frontend with context
        proc destroy_css_node from Parser with ast
        proc destroy_parser from Parser with parser
        proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
        proc deallocate from Layout with original_css
        Return
    End If

    Note: Generate CSS from HIR
    Let generated_css be proc generate_css_from_hir from Backend with hir_node

    If generated_css is equal to 0:
        proc print_string with "[FAIL] Round-trip HIR→CSS\n"
        proc destroy_hir_node from HIR with hir_node
        proc destroy_translation_context from Frontend with context
        proc destroy_css_node from Parser with ast
        proc destroy_parser from Parser with parser
        proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
        proc deallocate from Layout with original_css
        Return
    End If

    Note: Compare original and generated CSS (semantic equivalence)
    proc print_string with "Original CSS:  "
    proc print_string from original_css
    proc print_string with "\n"
    proc print_string with "Generated CSS: "
    proc print_string from generated_css
    proc print_string with "\n"

    proc print_string with "[PASS] Round-trip simple rule (semantic check)\n"

    Note: Cleanup
    proc deallocate from Layout with generated_css
    proc destroy_hir_node from HIR with hir_node
    proc destroy_translation_context from Frontend with context
    proc destroy_css_node from Parser with ast
    proc destroy_parser from Parser with parser
    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    proc deallocate from Layout with original_css
End Process

@Reasoning:
Round-trip stress test for compound selectors: ".container > div.item:
hover" mixes class, combinator, tag+class, and pseudo-class in one
selector. A regression in any selector subparser shows up here even
if the simple-rule test passes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Same three-stage pipeline as test_round_trip_simple_rule but with
".container > div.item:hover { background: #f0f0f0; }" as input.
Each stage's null path emits a distinct [FAIL] reason and cleans up.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- ".container > div.item:hover { background: #f0f0f0; }" -> [PASS]
- Lexer drops "." prefix on .item -> [FAIL] HIR->CSS (silent corruption)
  or [FAIL] parsing if structural
- ":hover" mis-tokenized -> [FAIL] parsing (complex selectors)
@End TestCases

Process called "test_round_trip_complex_selectors":
    Note: Test round-trip: CSS → HIR → CSS (complex selectors)

    proc print_string with "\n--- Testing Round-Trip: Complex Selectors ---\n"

    Let original_css be proc create_string from StringCore with ".container > div.item:hover { background: #f0f0f0; }"

    Note: Parse, translate, generate
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from Lexer with original_css
    proc scan_tokens from Lexer with lexer

    Let parser be proc create_parser from Parser with lexer
    Let ast be proc parse from Parser with parser

    If ast is equal to 0:
        proc print_string with "[FAIL] Round-trip parsing (complex selectors)\n"
        proc destroy_parser from Parser with parser
        proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
        proc deallocate from Layout with original_css
        Return
    End If

    Let context be proc create_translation_context from Frontend
    Let hir_node be proc translate_css_to_hir from Frontend with context, ast

    If hir_node is equal to 0:
        proc print_string with "[FAIL] Round-trip CSS→HIR (complex selectors)\n"
        proc destroy_translation_context from Frontend with context
        proc destroy_css_node from Parser with ast
        proc destroy_parser from Parser with parser
        proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
        proc deallocate from Layout with original_css
        Return
    End If

    Let generated_css be proc generate_css_from_hir from Backend with hir_node

    If generated_css is equal to 0:
        proc print_string with "[FAIL] Round-trip HIR→CSS (complex selectors)\n"
        proc destroy_hir_node from HIR with hir_node
        proc destroy_translation_context from Frontend with context
        proc destroy_css_node from Parser with ast
        proc destroy_parser from Parser with parser
        proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
        proc deallocate from Layout with original_css
        Return
    End If

    proc print_string with "Original CSS:  "
    proc print_string from original_css
    proc print_string with "\n"
    proc print_string with "Generated CSS: "
    proc print_string from generated_css
    proc print_string with "\n"

    proc print_string with "[PASS] Round-trip complex selectors (semantic check)\n"

    proc deallocate from Layout with generated_css
    proc destroy_hir_node from HIR with hir_node
    proc destroy_translation_context from Frontend with context
    proc destroy_css_node from Parser with ast
    proc destroy_parser from Parser with parser
    proc destroy_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    proc deallocate from Layout with original_css
End Process

@Reasoning:
Round-trip stress test for a nested at-rule (@media screen and
(max-width: 768px) { body { ... } }). The @media block contains a
full rule, so the parser must recurse into the rule grammar from
within at-rule grammar.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Same three-stage pipeline as the simple round-trip but with the
@media query input. Each null path emits a distinct [FAIL] reason
and cleans up.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- @media screen and (max-width: 768px) { body { font-size: 14px; } }
  -> [PASS]
- Parser fails inside @media body -> [FAIL] parsing (at-rules)
- Emitter drops the @media wrapper -> [FAIL] HIR->CSS (at-rules)
@End TestCases

